From: warsaw@nlm.nih.gov (Barry A. Warsaw)
Subject: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Reply-To: warsaw@nlm.nih.gov (Barry A. Warsaw)
Date: 06 Dec 1993 17:52:07 GMT


>>>>> "KB" == Kevin Brown <kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com> writes:

    KB> Why do people have so much trouble figuring out attributions?
    KB> Mario did *not* wrongly attribute to you something that
    KB> someone else wrote.  Take a look at the above.  Notice that
    KB> there is one attribution mark before each line of your article
    KB> that I'm responding to, two attribution marks before Mario's,
    KB> three before Glenn Pinkerton's.  Your article that Glenn
    KB> Pinkerton responded to would have 4 attribution marks before
    KB> it, but no lines with that many marks in front of them are to
    KB> be found.  Thus, what you wrote did not appear at all.  The
    KB> text you think is being attributed to you was (correctly)
    KB> attributed to Glenn Pinkerton.

Exactly the sort of (common) mistake non-nested attributions like what
you see above are supposed to reduce.  Some folks dislike them - like
every other religious issue, people have TOHO (their own humble
opinions) - and that's cool, but its usually pretty easy to figure out
exactly what text is being attributed to what person.

Oh, and for one implementation of non-nested citations in an Emacs
environment, see Supercite (1/2 :-).

